Nov 24, 1865"},{"short":"Confederate Kin IV (forthcoming) — biographical sketch"},{"short":"Antietam: Maj Thomas Talcott (aotw.org)"},{"short":"General Robert E Lee Staff Officers 1862 Antietam Campaign (americancivilwar.com)"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["military","civil_war","engineering"],"notable_blurb":"Colonel on Lee's staff at Appomattox; engineer"},"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Civil Engineer (Pre-War)","organization":"Ohio and Mississippi Railroad Company","end_year":1861,"notes":"Pre-Civil War railroad engineering career."},{"role":"Civil Engineer & Railroad Superintendent (Post-War)","organization":"Richmond and Danville Railroad","start_year":1865,"notes":"After Appomattox, resumed his profession of Civil Engineer and took charge of the Richmond and Danville Railroad as Superintendent and Engineer. Per Talcott Genealogy: 'after the close of the war resumed his profession of Civil Engineer which he had given up for a position in the Confederate army.'"},{"role":"Co-developer, Bon Air community","organization":"Bon Air, Chesterfield County, Virginia (with father Andrew Talcott)","notes":"TMR and his father Andrew planned and developed the Bon Air, Virginia community south of Richmond after the war."}],"military_service":[{"war":"American Civil War","rank":"Colonel (CSA) — terminal","unit":"1st Regiment of Engineer Troops, Confederate States Army","allegiance":"Confederate","service_years":"1861-1865","notes":"Career CSA service from secession to Appomattox:\n- May 23, 1861: Commissioned Captain in Virginia army; assigned to defenses of lower James River.\n- Oct 7, 1861: Commissioned First Lieutenant in regular CSA Army; Acting Chief Engineer of Department of Norfolk under Gen. Benjamin Huger.\n- Feb 1, 1862: Sent to Roanoke Island to inspect/report on defenses; joined defense against Burnside's attack. Taken prisoner; paroled.\n- ~March 1, 1862: Exchanged.\n- March 12, 1862: Promoted to Captain CSA; Chief Engineer of Department of Norfolk.\n- April 21, 1862: Commissioned Aide-de-Camp to the General-in-Chief of the CSA with rank of Major of Cavalry; assigned to staff of Gen. Robert E. Lee.\n- July 25, 1863: Promoted to Lieutenant Colonel.\n- April 4, 1864: Appointed Colonel of the 1st Regiment of Engineer Troops.\n- April 9, 1865: Surrendered with Lee at Appomattox Court House.\nEngagements: Battles around Richmond spring/summer 1862; Second Manassas/Bull Run; Sharpsburg/Antietam; Fredericksburg; Chancellorsville (1862-63); Army of Northern Virginia 1864 campaign (1st Engineers posted at Guiney's Station guarding supply depot during Wilderness, did not participate); active in defense of Petersburg summer 1864 - winter 1864-65; retreat to Appomattox.\nHis engineers fired the final volley for the Army of Northern Virginia just before Lee surrendered to Grant.\n\nRE Lee's testimonial (Nov 24, 1865, Lexington VA): 'Col. T.M.R. Talcott entered the Confederate service at the commencement of the war and performed valuable service in the Norfolk district as Captain of Engineers. In 1862 he accepted a position on my staff where his professional ability, boldness in the field and systematic industry were conspicuous. He continued in this position until promoted to the command of the 1st Regt of Engineer soldiers in the army of N. Virginia, in which capacity he served till the end of the war and was particularly useful in the campaign of 1864 and during the winter of 1864-5. His whole career in the army of N. Va. was marked by ability, zeal, devotion and integrity.' Signed: R.E. LEE.","war_id":"WAR006"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Fired the last volley before Lee's surrender","body":"He served on Robert E. Lee's personal staff from April 1862, eventually commanding the 1st Confederate Engineer Regiment as Colonel. His regiment fired the final volley for the Army of Northern Virginia in the hours before Lee's surrender at Appomattox."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Lee called his mother 'the Beautiful Talcott'","body":"His father Andrew was one of Robert E. Lee's closest friends from their U.S. Army Corps of Engineers days, and Lee shared a long affectionate friendship with his mother Harriet — whom he called 'the Beautiful Talcott.' That family connection eased his path onto Lee's personal staff in 1862."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Post-war Richmond railroad superintendent and engineer","body":"After Appomattox he resumed civil engineering — running the Richmond and Danville Railroad as Superintendent and Engineer. With his father Andrew he planned and developed the Bon Air community south of Richmond."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Recipient of Lee's farewell General Orders No. 9","body":"Lee's farewell address — General Orders No. 9, dated April 10, 1865 — was issued at Appomattox to him as commander of the 1st Regiment Engineer Troops. The Morgan Library and Museum holds an official copy and a contemporary manuscript."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Outlived nearly all twenty-four of Lee's staff officers","body":"He was one of twenty-four officers who served on Lee's personal staff during the war. At his death in 1920 at age 82, he was one of the last two surviving members."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X02149","display_label":"was his father-in-law"},{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X02150","display_label":"was his mother-in-law"}],"bio":{"title":"Colonel","first_name":"Thomas","middle_name":"Mann Randolph","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"nickname":"\"TMR\"","display_name":"Col. Thomas Mann Randolph Talcott","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780755818/Colonel_Talcott_avfkvs.jpg"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":["DOC012"],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST035"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"slug":"thomas-talcott-1838"},"T01883":{"id"